# Test coverage floor (awaits ADR-09)

## Rule
Until ADR-09 resolves, the interim rule is **diff coverage > 0 on net-new code paths**:

- Any net-new function / method / class must have at least one test that exercises its happy path.
- Any new branch (if / else / case) that is not trivially unreachable must have at least one test.
- Bug fixes include a regression test that fails without the fix.
- Legacy-code refactors keep existing tests green; coverage neither grows nor falls.

When ADR-09 accepts a percentage floor, `test-agent` replaces this interim rule.

## Why
Zero-coverage PRs accumulate technical debt silently. A diff-coverage floor is cheap to enforce and produces the ratchet toward whichever percentage ADR-09 eventually picks.

## Constraints
- `test-agent` runs the repo's test command and checks new code paths for coverage.
- Integration tests count; end-to-end tests do not (they prove the system works, not that the unit is covered).
- Intentionally untested paths (e.g., trivial pass-through, logging) require a one-line comment explaining why.
- Commented-out tests count as zero coverage and block the gate.

## Examples

### Good
> Bug fix for tenant-filter bypass in fb-rates-go: repository method change + a new `*_test.go` case that calls the method with a foreign tenant and asserts the filter is enforced.

### Bad
> Bug fix with no accompanying test; `test-agent` blocks.

